BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (02)
*********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Sat, 2 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU, DG Health & Consumer Protection, accessed 2 Sep 2006 [edited]
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/adns/table_11_2006/adns_010906_en.pdf>


Animal disease notification system
----------------------------------
According to the 1 Sep 2006 update of table 11 (animal disease situation
per country and per disease), the total number of bluetongue outbreaks
reported by European Union member states during the period 1 Jan 2006 to 1
Sep 2006 was 137.

These outbreaks were reported from the following countries:
Country / No of outbreaks / last date of confirmation
Belgium / 65 / 31 Aug 2006
Germany / 40 / 29 Aug 2006
France / 1 / 30 Aug 2006
Netherlands / 31 / 30 Aug 2006

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[France has notified, in the meantime, 2 additional cases; see next item. -
Mod.AS]

******
[2]
Date: Sat, 2 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: French Min of Agriculture web-site, accessed 2 Sep 2006 [edited]
<http://www.agriculture.gouv.fr/spip/>


The French Ministry of Agriculture has issued 3 press releases, referring
to bluetongue outbreaks diagnosed in cows near the Belgian frontier.

The 1st case occurred in Brognon, Lat 49:55:46N, Lon4:17:08E; zoomable map
available at
<http://www.multimap.com/map//map/browse.cgi?lat=49.9293&lon=4.2856&scale=100000&icon=x>.

It involved a cow with slight clinical signs (lameness). The press release,
in French, is available at
<http://www.agriculture.gouv.fr/spip/leministere.leministrelecabinet.communiquesdepresse_a6317.html>.

The 2nd case was diagnosed in a clinically unaffected cow at Beaurieux,
Lat: 50:10:33N ; Lon: 4:07:38E. Zoomable map available at
<http://www.multimap.com/map//map/browse.cgi?lat=50.1759&lon=4.1272&scale=100000&icon=x>.

The press release, in French, is available at
<http://www.agriculture.gouv.fr/spip/leministere.leministrelecabinet.communiquesdepresse_a6318.html>.

The 3rd case was diagnosed in a clinically unaffected cow at Hierges, Lat:
50:06:19N , Lon: 4:44:27E. Zoomable map available at
<http://www.multimap.com/map//map/browse.cgi?lat=50.1054&lon=4.7409&scale=100000&icon=x>.

The press release, in French, is available at
<http://www.agriculture.gouv.fr/spip/leministere.leministrelecabinet.communiquesdepresse_a6323.html>

The 2 last cases have been detected in the framework of the surveillance
for bluetongue within the 150 km zone. [It is not clear whether the
diagnosis was based upon virus isolation/detection or serology. - Mod.AS]

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Interested subscribers may consider reading the detailed reports of
Belgium, Germany, and the Netherlands, presented during the last meeting of
SCoFCAH (EU's Standing Committee on Food Chain and Animal Health) held in
Brussels on 28 Aug 2006 (recommended). The reports include descriptions of
the outbreaks, their chronology, maps, results of monitoring and
surveillance activities within and outside the 150-km protection zone,
pictures demonstrating the clinical signs in bovines and ovines, and
additional valuable information. They are accessible at the following URLs:
Belgium -
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/bluetongue_scofcah_belgium.pdf>

Germany -
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/bluetongue_scofcah_germany.pdf>

the Netherlands -
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/bluetongue_scofcah_netherlands.pdf>.

We are grateful to Mary Marshall for bringing the said URLs to our
attention. - Mod.AS]
